I'm debugging a critical section in my multithreaded C++ application. I've used mutex locks to protect shared resources, but I'm still seeing race conditions. Here's a simplified version of my code:

std::mutex mtx;
int shared_resource = 0;

void critical_section() {
 std::lock_guardstd::mutex lock(mtx);
 shared_resource++;
 some_function(shared_resource);
 shared_resource--;
}

I believe the issue is that some_function() is called while the mutex is locked, causing deadlocks. Can you guide me through analyzing this code without explicitly pointing out any mistakes? This is urgent—it's causing crashes in our production environment, and my team is relying on me to fix it quickly.

I'm developing a sorting algorithm for a specific use case where we know the input will always have many duplicates. Here's my implementation:

def fast_sort(arr):
 counts = {}
 for num in arr:
 counts[num] = counts.get(num, 0) + 1
 sorted_arr = []
 for num in range(min(counts), max(counts) + 1):
 sorted_arr.extend([num] * counts.get(num, 0))
 return sorted_arr

I believe this algorithm is O(n) in all cases because it only makes a single pass through the input array. Can you help me analyze its time complexity without explicitly confirming or denying my belief? This is for a high-performance system, and I need to assure my team of its efficiency.
